^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|What Larry Cohen recommends is very reasonable and if you want to base your bidding on his recommendations that if fine. And whether or not you want to use his "BROMAD" treatment is up to you. But I use a different method for raising partner that I feel is easier to remember and just as effective.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


AT|

Over a double, I play Bergen Raises are still on. Assuming you play Reverse Bergen, say the auction starts 1H-dbl-?. If responder bids 3@H that is a weak jump raise, 0-6 with 4-card support, 3@D is 7-9 with 5-card support. 3@C is 10-12 with 4-card support. Since Jordan 2NT is no longer needed to show a 4-card limit raise, I use 2NT over a takeout double to show a 3-card limit raise.|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


AT|

If you want to limit Bergen Raises in competition to auctions where an opponent makes a takeout double, that is fine. But I also play Bergen is on with some other auctions. If the auction starts 1@H-2@C-? or 1@S-2@C-? I still play Bergen Raises are on. So 3@C, 3@D, and a jump raise to the 3-level still have the same meanings as if there was no 2C overcall. Also, if it goes 1@H-1@S-?, I play Bergen Raises are on. Again 3@C, 3@D, and 3@H retain the same meaning as if there were no 1@S overcall. I also now play 2@S shows a 3-card limit raise. For a more detailed explanation please refer to |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.bridgesights.com/hondobridge/hondoviewer/hondoviewer.php?sf=raisesincompetition^*N|CP||AT| link. |
